\section{Integration with Python Computations}

You can use Python to generate bit strings programmatically:

\begin{pycode}
# Generate a simple pattern
bits = "010110"
print(r"\textbf{Generated bit string:} \texttt{" + bits + "}")
\end{pycode}

And draw the corresponding path:

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \lpDeclarePath{Analyzed}{010110}
  \drawLatticePath[brown, very thick]{Analyzed}
  \draw[help lines] (0,0) grid (6,6);
\end{tikzpicture}
\quad
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \lpDeclarePath{Analyzed}{010110}
  \drawLatticePath[brown, very thick, lplpath/label upmarks]{Analyzed}
  \draw[help lines] (0,0) grid (6,6);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\section{Caching and Performance}

The package automatically caches computed coordinate data in the \texttt{lp-cache/} directory. After the first PythonTeX run, subsequent compilations reuse cached data for improved performance.

The cache files are identified by content-based hashing, so changing a permutation automatically triggers recomputation while unchanged paths load instantly.

